description:
&lt;p&gt;Contract type: permanent&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hours: 37.5 hours per week&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A unique and exciting opportunity has arisen to join the University of York and York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust as a Clinical Teaching Fellow (Nursing).&lt;br /&gt;The Clinical Teaching Fellow is an innovative joint appointment between the Department of Health Sciences at the University of York, and York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust. Splitting time 60:40 between the University and York Hospital, we are seeking appoint two Clinical Teaching Fellows who will play an important role in the development and delivery of teaching to nursing students on the University of York’s education programmes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Role&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Working with the academic teaching team at the University of York, and the corporate nursing team at York Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, the Clinical Teaching Fellows will:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Act as a conduit between the Trust and University to promote effective partnership working and be a valuable resource for staff and students requiring advice or guidance on issues relating to nursing education.&lt;br /&gt;• Contribute to the learning, support and assessment of students in both practice and academic environments, including those related to the development of clinical skills and competencies through simulated practice &lt;br /&gt;• Develop and apply innovative and appropriate teaching techniques and material which create interest, understanding and enthusiasm amongst students &lt;br /&gt;• Carry out on-going curriculum review, including module content and materials and contribute to the development of teaching and learning strategies &lt;br /&gt;• Ensure that the student experience is of the highest quality and enables the greatest benefit from the individual clinical learning experience&lt;br /&gt;• Ensure that the Trust values, objectives and shared commitments are integral to all areas of development and delivery&lt;br /&gt;• Liaise with practice assessors, practice supervisors, HEIs and other appropriate colleagues to assist with students in difficulty to develop remedial action plans&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span&gt;Skills, Experience &amp; Qualification needed&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;• Current registration with NMC as a Registered Nurse&lt;br /&gt;• Degree in Nursing or related Healthcare &lt;br /&gt;• Recognised teaching certificate, e.g. ILS/ALS instructor, GIC course, ENB 998, Cert Ed, PGCE&lt;br /&gt;• Significant post registration experience in a clinical setting&lt;br /&gt;• Knowledge of NMC standards for student supervision and assessment, and delivery of safe and effective learning experiences for nursing students in practice&lt;br /&gt;• Experience of facilitating learning, teaching and assessment in clinical practice&lt;br /&gt;• Able to demonstrate collaborative working with MDT colleagues in a variety of clinical and academic settings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Interview date: TBC&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;It&#39;s not just the area that&#39;s a great draw, as well: as a member of our team, you’ll have access to one of the most generous and comprehensive pension schemes in the UK, a minimum of 27 days annual leave (on top of Bank Holidays) and an award-winning package of staff benefits (see link on the right).&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
